{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_anaconda_ver01/data/sn85053044/00517178135/1949011401/0012.xml":{"full_text":"THE MDWHIIIt CHEF\nJohn E. Davies, Editor and Owner\nA weekly newspaper published\nevery Friday at Browning, Glacier\nCounty, Montana.\nEntered as 2nd class matter July 15,\n1931 at the postoffice at Browning,\nMontana, under act of March 3, 1879.\nSubscription $2.00 year in advance\nGENERLLY FAIR, WITH\nFAINT THUNDER\nThere may have been another\nturn of the year when more news\nprint was filled with estimates of\nthe economic picture and \u201cgues\nstimates\u201d of the next 12 months,\nbut we can\u2019t recall it. The econ\nomists have been interviewed and\npolled, captains of industry and\nfinance quoted, and a mile or two\nof figures gathered into neat\ncharts and tables,\nA remarkable preponderance\nof this opinion adds up to a pre\ndiction that 1949 will be another\nyear of prosperity, high employ\nment, good profits, and big pro\nduction despite a moderate slide\nin all these things from 1947-48\npeaks. The experts won\u2019t even\ncall that a recession, let alone a\ndepression. But being experts,\nand conscientious at that, they\nadd a lot of becauses, its, and\nbuts. And it is these complicated\nqualifications that are really im\nportant.\nFar be it from us to try outex\nperting the experts. But it might\nbe helpful to ri s k a few steps\nalong the thin edge of oversim\nplification and try to get things\ninto a focus we can grasp our\nselves. This is how it looks to us:\nM ITSTRUE...HEREANDNOW! M\nI New Hudson I\nH| F <>R ONLY H|\n$2557 61\nDELIVERED HERE FULLY EQMmD\n1. iMMdtato Mmtt <mm aUds\nX Cab a ttaw\n4. WBb a whbal\n5. Gad sllivaw H yw ba, a iraMa\nParkway Garage\nBrowning, Montana\nMb. Price aaay\nHo\u00ab <AorgM>\nSPECIALS\nPeas can 2 2 for 29c\nQuality Rice 2 lbs. for 19c\nEgg Noodles Quaker 4 oz. 5 c\nTry Our Delicious\nHome-made Sausage.\n\nThe United StatM is likely to\ncontinue prosperous (and, it\nshould be said, somewhat inflat\ned) because it is realizing its tre\nmendous productive capacity; be\ncause through wide distribution\nof profits, wages, and salaries\nthere is still a prospect of buy\ning power to support that pro\nductivity; because and shrinking\naway of that buying power is\nlikely to be balanced by aid to\nEurope and expenditures for na\ntional defense; because, in spite\nof production\u2019s more than catch-,\ning up in many lines, a great\nbacklog of demand still persists\nin the basic industries.\nSeveral factors, likewise should\nwork against the expected mod\nerate descent\u2019s becoming a tail\nspin. For instance: There has\nbeen no speculative boom on the\nstock market. A great many\nfirms are financing expans\nion out of their own profit-built\nreserves, and thus are not deep\nin debt. The mood of business\ngenerally is cautious, not over\nconfident. A sizable cushion of\npersonal savings still remains.\nThe American people and their\ngovernment both have attained a\ndegree of economic literacy since\n1929 that amazes the economists.\nNot only that, but the battle over\nthe government\u2019s responsibility\nto take countermeasures against\na depression has already been\nfought out, and there now exists\nbasic legislation which charts the\nway.\nNow for the somber side\u2014the\nifs and the could-be\u2019s: In a num\nber of lines production now has\noutstripped consumption. In\nsome, supply plus high price has\nTHE BROWNING CHIEF\nMontana....\nNames .Places\nSTATE FORESTS\nBy Rutledge Parker, State, Forester.\nThe nineteenth session (1925) of the State Legislature\ncreated seven State Forests, namely: Stillwater and Coal\nCreek in Flathead County, Swan River in Lake County,\nThompson River in Sanders County, Clearwater in Missoula\nCounty, Sula in Ravalli County and Lincoln in Lewis and Clark\nCounty. These seven forests comprise a total of 235,876 acres.\nIn addition, there are 450.124 acres of scattered lands, mostly\ncommon school sections 16 and 36, 150,000 acres of which are\nclassed as non-commercial forest lands, total 686,000 acres.\nThe State has collected from sale of its timber $3,000,000.00\nduring the past 40 years. If the future cut of State timber\ncontinues on about the same basis, the supply is sufficient for\na period of 80 years, which would produce an additional in\ncome of $7,000,000.00, or more. Land uses, such as the\ngrazing of livestock, will very materially increase the annual\nincome from $10,000.00 to $15,000.00 per year or more. Due\nto the heavy demand for war purposes, income from the\nState Forests for the fiscal years 1944 and 1945 was greater\nthan any previous years.\nThe State Forests are included in a part of the land grant\nto Montana by the Federal Government. All income from the\nState Forests are allocated to the common schools and other\nState institutions mentioned in the land grant.\nAll of the State-owned forest lands are protected from the\nravages of forest fires at a cost of approximately $20,000.00\nper year.\nAnaconda Copper Mining Company\n\u201cWork for a Greater and More Prosperous Montana\u201d.\nThis is a project that should include all Montanans.\npulled away from demand. La\nbor\u2019s reaction (so far) to these\nwarning signs has been to talk\nabout a fourth round of wage in\ncreases and a shorter work week.\nIndustry\u2019s answer (so far) seems\nto be to keep prices up, cut pro\nduction, and lay off workers.\nThere have been layoffs since\nNovenber 1 in at least nine in\ndustries\u2014small in total, but their\neffect could spread. Two months\nago the average work week drop-\nped below 40 hours for the first:\ntime since 1940.\nGranted that labor has been\ntalking moderately, and business\nhas cut a few prices. Here, sm;.ll\nas it is as yet, is the same vicious\ncircle that spun into a maelstrom\nof national tragedy in the 1930'5:\nPrices (and wages) held rigidly\nhigh lose buyers, tap no new res\nervoir of consumers: the lack of\nj buyers lessens demand; the\nshrinking demand contracts pro\nduction and throws wage earners\nout of jobs; every worker with-\nI out a job means one more con\nsumer without money to buy\nwith, and the grim spiral goes\ndown and down.\nGovernment can amelioraie\nsuch a calamity; it cannot wholly\nprevent one. We are by no means\npredicting a depression, major or\nminor. But until American busi\nness and organized labor both\nstart acting as though they were\naware of this danger we shall not\nbe quite so comfortable as the\nexperts. \u2014Christian Science Mon\nitor.\nNOTICE\nWe will reopen\nfor business on\nMonday, Janu\nary I 7 at 7 a. m.\nFollick\nGrill\nWe Appreciate Your\nPatronage\nConrad Credit Assc.\nAnnual Election\nSet For Jan. 15\nStockholders of the Conrad\nProduction Credit Association\nand their guests will celebrate\ntheir fifteenth anniversary witii\na banquet and business session\nat the Conrad Hotel in Conrad on\nSaturday, January 15 at 12 noon.\nThree directors will be elected\nat this meeting, one from Glac\nier County, one from Toole Coun\nty and one from Liberty Coun\nty.\nAt a recent meeting of the\nnominating committee the fol\nlowing were nominated: R. W.\nWe are proud to announce our\nappointment as dealer for\nKaiser and Frazer\ng Motor Cars\nin Browning and\nvicinity\nes, we ve joined the swing to Kaiser-Frazer! From now on, the value\nproved Kaiser and Frazer, with more than 100 new refinements and improve\nments for 1949, will be on display in our showrooms; In addition, our ser\nvice department will now operate exclusively under Kaiser-Frazer factory ap\nproved methods, as a guarantee of fast, efficient and economical service for\nmakes of cars. Drop in soon. Let\u2019s get acquainted.\nBROWNING MOTORS\nwERYKiEj Chas. Peterson and Tom House, Proprs.\nnru iv.\nMEKER\n\u00bbe sonny x A\nyou saved\nArgue as you will about high prices; I\ninflation good times being here for\never this we know... You\u2019ll Never Be\nSorry You Saved. You\u2019ll forget the sac\nrifices you made it won\u2019t matter\nwhether good times stay or not... you\u2019ll\nhave money in the bank, and that\u2019s H\nAlways something to be thankful for I U\nThe First National Bank\nof Browning d\nDesignated Depository of Indian Funds\nMember Federal Deposit Insurance.Gorporation H\n===SAVE AT THIS\nHarper, Browning and Percy\nDeWolfe, Babb, from Glacier\nCounty. Gordon Christian,\nShelby, and Melvin Underdal,\nShelby, from Toole County.\nDavid James, Joplin and J. H.\nMcDcDowoll, Chester, from Lib\nerty County.\nCharts showing the progress\nof the association and the re\nserves built up will be ex\nplained by the secretary, Eugene\nL. Robinson; J. W. Bradley of\nthe Production Credit Corpora\ntion of Spokane, will give a resu\nme of the 15 years of service to\nthe farmers and ranchers of Gla\ncier, Toole, Pondera and Liberty\nCounties.\nFirst Tin Can Patent\nAn English inventor patented the\nfirst tin can in 1910. This \u201ccanister\"\nwas cut out and soldered by hand\nand a circular hole was left in the\ntop. After it was filled, the hole was\nclosed by soldering on a tin plate\ndisc. An expert could produce five or\nsix cans per hour. Since that time,\ncontinued improvements in can mak\ning have advanced the number to\n20,000 per hour.\nCARD OF THANKS\nFor the many acts of kindness\nand expressions of sympathy in\nour behalf in the d e a t h of our\nfather and grandfather, the late\nMicheal LaSorte, we take this\nmeans of expressing our deep\ngraditude.\nMr. and Mrs. Joe LaSorte and\nfamily.\nMr. and Mrs. Frank LaSorte\nand family.\nWho\u2019s Your Tailor?\nFall and Winter Tailormade\nSuits for Ladies and Gents\n$45 and Up\nWestern Tailors\nBy the Bank Building\nWhere You Are Served by a\nTailor with a Diploma,\nJohn Sharp.","height":"20416","width":"14612"}}
